                    <abstract lang="eng">Using video-recordings from a real-world eld trial of a mu-seum guide robot, we show how a robot&apos;s gaze influences the visitors&apos; state of participation in group constellations. Then, we compare the robot&apos;s conduct to a human tour guide&apos;s gaze strategies. We argue that a robot system, to deal with real-world everyday situations, needs to be equipped with knowledge about interactional coordination, incremental processing and strategies for pro-actively shaping the users&apos; conduct.</abstract>
